Threat Model Name: AAST Financial Portal

Owner: Adam Tamer,Youssef Mohamed ElBadr

Reviewer: Dr.Mohamed Seif

Contributors: Mahmoud Khaled,Ahmed ElBahnasawy

Description: The system is a robust and secure architecture designed to support multiple categories of users, including staff, remote staff, students, and administrators. Each group of users interacts with the system through distinct channels that ensure secure communication. For instance, remote staff access the network through a VPN gateway using HTTPS/VPN protocols, while students primarily connect via HTTPS. The architecture emphasizes security, efficiency, and role-based access control. At the heart of the system lies the web portal, which serves as the central platform for user interaction. This portal is designed to support secure communication through IPsec protocols and integrates seamlessly with other critical components such as the payment gateway for financial transactions and the monitoring server for performance tracking and health monitoring. It also connects to a Group Policy Object (GPO) to enforce organizational policies and manage user access. The VPN gateway is an essential component that ensures secure remote access for remote staff by establishing encrypted connections. For authentication, the system uses two separate Active Directory (AD) services: the Students’ AD, located in the DMZ, provides authentication for external student access, while the Staff AD resides within the internal network to authenticate and manage staff credentials securely. The application server is responsible for handling business logic and facilitating communication between users and other system components, such as the database server. Data storage and retrieval are managed by a database server, which also interacts with backup storage through SFTP connections. These backup operations take place in a restricted zone to ensure data security and recovery in case of system failures. To maintain system integrity and confidentiality, the architecture relies on a combination of secure communication protocols, including HTTPS for web traffic, IPsec for encrypted network communications, and SFTP for secure file transfers. Overall, the system is designed to ensure seamless communication, strict access control, and robust data management across all user roles and components.

Assumptions: The architecture assumes that all communications between system components and users are encrypted using secure protocols such as HTTPS, IPsec, and SFTP. These protocols are critical to protecting sensitive data and ensuring the confidentiality and integrity of transactions. The placement of the Students’ AD in the DMZ assumes that this segment is isolated from the internal network, offering additional layers of protection against external threats. Similarly, the restricted zone housing the database server and backup storage is assumed to be inaccessible to unauthorized users, with strict access controls in place. Staff and remote staff are assumed to be using secure, organization-provided devices or applications when accessing the system. This ensures that endpoints connecting to the network are trusted and free from vulnerabilities. Finally, network segmentation is assumed to function as designed, ensuring that restricted zones and sensitive components are protected from general user access.

External Dependencies: University administrative staff must have the current VPN software installed on their remote system, and be using a current/supported web browser version. Students must have a current/supported web browser version. Remote access internet access should at least be providing 10Mbps broadband service with a stable connection, and either wired or wireless is acceptable. All remote users must have up-to-date anti-malware protection running actively on their systems.

1. Elevation Using Impersonation  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:Monitoring Server may be able to impersonate the context of Admin in order to gain additional privilege.
Justification:The Monitoring Server should only be able to read logs or metrics, not perform operations requiring elevated privileges.

2. Potential Data Repudiation by Monitoring Server  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Repudiation
Description:Monitoring Server claims that it did not receive data from a source outside the trust boundary. Consider using logging or auditing to record the source, time, and summary of the received data.
Justification:1-Use secure, append-only logging mechanisms to record all interactions with the Monitoring Server, ensuring logs cannot be tampered with or deleted. Implement centralized logging systems to securely store logs that can be audited later. 2-Use integrity checks, such as hashing or checksums, to verify the authenticity and integrity of logs and received data.

3. Potential Process Crash or Stop for Monitoring Server  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:Monitoring Server crashes, halts, stops or runs slowly; in all cases violating an availability metric.
Justification:1-Design the Monitoring Server with fault tolerance in mind. Set up automatic system recovery mechanisms, such as process watchdogs, that can detect a failure and automatically restart the server or process to minimize downtime. 2-Use load balancing to distribute traffic across multiple Monitoring Servers, ensuring that no single server becomes overwhelmed and crashes.

4. Data Flow Monitoring access Is Potentially Interrupted  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:An external agent interrupts data flowing across a trust boundary in either direction.
Justification:1-Implement multiple redundant network paths to ensure data flow remains uninterrupted even if one path is attacked or becomes unavailable. This can include load balancing, failover mechanisms, and automatic rerouting of traffic. 2-Utilize an IDPS to monitor traffic patterns and identify abnormal behaviors indicative of attacks attempting to interrupt data flow.

5. Monitoring Server May be Subject to Elevation of Privilege Using Remote Code Execution  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:Admin may be able to remotely execute code for Monitoring Server.
Justification:1-Ensure that the Monitoring Server is up-to-date with the latest security patches, especially those addressing vulnerabilities that could be exploited for remote code execution (RCE). 2-Restrict access to the Monitoring Server through strict access controls, and use network segmentation to limit the server’s exposure to potential attackers.

6. Elevation by Changing the Execution Flow in Monitoring Server  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:An attacker may pass data into Monitoring Server in order to change the flow of program execution within Monitoring Server to the attacker's choosing.
Justification:1-Ensure that all inputs to the Monitoring Server are properly validated and sanitized to prevent data manipulation that could alter the execution flow. Implement strict input validation rules, especially for untrusted sources, to prevent any unauthorized changes to program behavior. 2-Ensure that only verified, signed code is allowed to execute on the Monitoring Server.

40. Risks from Logging  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:Log readers can come under attack via log files. Consider ways to canonicalize data in all logs. Implement a single reader for the logs, if possible, in order to reduce attack surface area. Be sure to understand and document log file elements which come from untrusted sources.
Justification:1- Implement a single, secure reader for logs to minimize potential entry points for attackers. 2-Implement data validation checks to ensure that log data from untrusted sources conforms to the expected format.

41. Potential SQL Injection Vulnerability for Database server  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:SQL injection is an attack in which malicious code is inserted into strings that are later passed to an instance of SQL Server for parsing and execution. Any procedure that constructs SQL statements should be reviewed for injection vulnerabilities because SQL Server will execute all syntactically valid queries that it receives. Even parameterized data can be manipulated by a skilled and determined attacker.
Justification:1-Ensures that user input is treated as data, not executable code, preventing malicious input from being executed. 2-Implement input validation on all user inputs, ensuring that data conforms to expected formats. Reject inputs that do not meet these criteria.

42. The Database server Data Store Could Be Corrupted  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:Data flowing across HTTPS/IPsec may be tampered with by an attacker. This may lead to corruption of Database server. Ensure the integrity of the data flow to the data store.
Justification:Ensure that data is encrypted end-to-end using robust protocols such as TLS for HTTPS and IPsec for network-level encryption. This ensures that the data remains secure during transmition and prevents tampering or eavesdropping by unauthorized entities.

43. Lower Trusted Subject Updates Logs  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Repudiation
Description:If you have trust levels, is anyone other outside of the highest trust level allowed to log? Letting everyone write to your logs can lead to repudiation problems. Only allow trusted code to log.
Justification:1-ensures that logging operations are restricted to trusted sources, minimizing the risk of tampering. 2-Use techniques like cryptographic signing of log entries to ensure that once a log entry is written, it cannot be altered. If logs are tampered with, the integrity signature will be invalidated, providing evidence of manipulation.

44. Data Logs from an Unknown Source  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Repudiation
Description:Do you accept logs from unknown or weakly authenticated users or systems? Identify and authenticate the source of the logs before accepting them.
Justification:Require authentication of all log sources before accepting logs into the centralized logging system.

45. Insufficient Auditing  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Repudiation
Description:Does the log capture enough data to understand what happened in the past? Do your logs capture enough data to understand an incident after the fact? Is such capture lightweight enough to be left on all the time? Do you have enough data to deal with repudiation claims? Make sure you log sufficient and appropriate data to handle a repudiation claims. You might want to talk to an audit expert as well as a privacy expert about your choice of data.
Justification:Ensure that logs capture sufficient contextual information, including user identity, timestamps, action details, and source IP addresses. This allows incidents to be traced and analyzed accurately.

46. Potential Weak Protections for Audit Data  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Repudiation
Description:Consider what happens when the audit mechanism comes under attack, including attempts to destroy the logs, or attack log analysis programs. Ensure access to the log is through a reference monitor, which controls read and write separately. Document what filters, if any, readers can rely on, or writers should expect
Justification:1-Ensure that access to logs is tightly controlled by separating read and write permissions. 2-Logs should be backed up regularly to ensure that they can be restored in case of tampering or destruction.

48. Weak Credential Storage  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Information Disclosure
Description:Credentials held at the server are often disclosed or tampered with and credentials stored on the client are often stolen. For server side, consider storing a salted hash of the credentials instead of storing the credentials themselves. If this is not possible due to business requirements, be sure to encrypt the credentials before storage, using an SDL-approved mechanism. For client side, if storing credentials is required, encrypt them and protect the data store in which they're stored
Justification:1-Strong encryption algorithms such as AES with a secure key management system must be used 2-Ensure that access to stored credentials is restricted to authorized personnel or services only

49. Potential Excessive Resource Consumption for Monitoring Server or Database server  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:Does Monitoring Server or Database server take explicit steps to control resource consumption? Resource consumption attacks can be hard to deal with, and there are times that it makes sense to let the OS do the job. Be careful that your resource requests don't deadlock, and that they do timeout.
Justification:1-On the Database Server, configure query timeouts to prevent long-running or inefficient queries from consuming too many resources 2-On the Monitoring Server, resource-heavy tasks (such as complex log analysis or data aggregation) could be limited to specific CPU cores or given time limits

64. Collision Attacks  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:Attackers who can send a series of packets or messages may be able to overlap data. For example, packet 1 may be 100 bytes starting at offset 0. Packet 2 may be 100 bytes starting at offset 25. Packet 2 will overwrite 75 bytes of packet 1. Ensure you reassemble data before filtering it, and ensure you explicitly handle these sorts of cases.
Justification:1-Implement logic to detect and discard overlapping segments or ensure the later packet overwrites previous data deterministically. 2-Implement strict rules to reject packets that do not conform to expected behaviors or include overlapping data.

65. Replay Attacks  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:Packets or messages without sequence numbers or timestamps can be captured and replayed in a wide variety of ways. Implement or utilize an existing communication protocol that supports anti-replay techniques (investigate sequence numbers before timers) and strong integrity.
Justification:1- All transmitted packets include unique sequence numbers to detect and prevent replay attacks. 2-Messages include timestamps to ensure they are processed only within an acceptable time window.
